Public health insurance in the Czech Republic:

- is mandatory for all citizens and permanent residents;
- is provided by the National Health Insurance Fund (VZP);
- covers a wide range of services, including basic medical care, specialist care, hospital care, maternity care, and dental care;
- is financed through a combination of payroll taxes and government subsidies;
- provides equal access to healthcare for all citizens and permanent residents, regardless of their income or social status;
- has a strong focus on preventive care and health promotion;
- is regularly evaluated and updated to ensure it meets the needs of the population;
- offers a wide range of additional services, such as spa treatment, physiotherapy, and psychological counselling.

Private health insurance in the Czech Republic:

- is optional and not mandatory for citizens or permanent residents;
- is provided by private health insurance companies;
- covers a wide range of services, but may vary depending on the policy;
- is financed through monthly premiums paid by the policyholder;
- allows policyholders to choose their own healthcare providers and hospitals;
- may offer additional benefits, such as shorter waiting times for treatment, private rooms in hospitals, and access to experimental treatments;
- is not regulated by the government to the same extent as public health insurance.
